<p id="p0085">It is usual to take the inverse of the removal rate (
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="M23" altimg="si14.svg">
   <mrow>
    <mi>q</mi>
    <mo linebreak="goodbreak" linebreakstyle="after">+</mo>
    <mi>γ</mi>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula>) or the recovery rate (
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="M24" altimg="si7.svg">
   <mrow>
    <mi>γ</mi>
    <mo>’</mo>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula>) as the unit of time, and the dimensionless time 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="M25" altimg="si20.svg">
   <mrow>
    <mi>t</mi>
    <mo>’</mo>
    <mo linebreak="goodbreak" linebreakstyle="after">=</mo>
    <msup>
     <mrow>
      <mrow>
       <mo stretchy="true">(</mo>
       <mrow>
        <mi>q</mi>
        <mo linebreak="badbreak">+</mo>
        <mi>γ</mi>
       </mrow>
       <mo stretchy="true">)</mo>
      </mrow>
     </mrow>
     <mrow>
      <mo>−</mo>
      <mn>1</mn>
     </mrow>
    </msup>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> and the reproduction number 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="M26" altimg="si21.svg">
   <mrow>
    <mi>R</mi>
    <mo linebreak="goodbreak" linebreakstyle="after">=</mo>
    <mi>β</mi>
    <mi>S</mi>
    <mo linebreak="goodbreak" linebreakstyle="after">/</mo>
    <mrow>
     <mo stretchy="true">(</mo>
     <mrow>
      <mi>q</mi>
      <mo linebreak="badbreak">+</mo>
      <mi>γ</mi>
     </mrow>
     <mo stretchy="true">)</mo>
    </mrow>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> are used in the analysis. However, these parameters are policy dependent and cannot be considered as an intrinsic time unit of the problem. In order to present results in the style that citizens and policy makers can easily understand, I take one day as the unit of time in this paper.
</p>
